7 SUMMARY
88 This bill extends the deadline by which the Department of Professional and Financial
99 Regulation, Bureau of Financial Institutions must publish a notice of a final order in a
1100 newspaper during the decision-making process on an application for a charter, branch,
1111 merger, acquisition, conversion, subsidiary formation or other similar request.
1122 Additionally, the bill eliminates certain administrative fees charged to financial institutions
1133 based on their volume of consumer loans. The bill also eliminates the alternative approval
1144 process that allows the board of directors of a mutual financial institution, subject to written
1155 approval of the Superintendent of Financial Institutions, to fix the rate of the directors' own
1166 compensation.
17 The bill provides that when a credit union chartered in this State participates in a loan,
18 the borrower must be a member of any one of the participating credit unions and any real
19 estate securing the loan need not be located in this State. The bill aligns the laws that permit
20 the disclosure of financial records to the Office of the Attorney General or a law
21 enforcement agency when a financial institution or credit union has reasonable cause to
22 believe that a disbursement requested by certain individuals may result in financial
23 exploitation of an individual with the provisions in the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 9-B,
24 section 245 by clarifying that the required age of such an individual is 65 years of age or
25 older and that individuals protected under the Adult Protective Services Act are included.
26 The bill changes the definition of "supervisory agency" for the laws governing confidential
27 financial records by adding the federal Consumer Financial Protection Bureau and
28 providing that any successor agency to an agency listed in the definition is considered to
29 be a supervisory agency.
